elements.name: element
comments: A generic html element.
The wzName, if present becames the first TEXTNODE of the html element.
You should find a proper schema element that extends this one for every valid html element.
In any case this element is not abstract and can be used for eventual missing html elements.
In this case must contain a name-value pair separated by a blank: name is
the html element name and value (optional), if present, is the first TEXTNODE of the element.

elements.name: html
comments: The root element.

elements.name: attribute
comments: Used for Html element attributes not declared in this schema.
The wzName must contain a name-value pair separated by a blank (value is optional).
Name is the attribute name and value, if not empty, is the attribute value.

elements.name: _dot
comments: short for <div class='${wzName}' [ attributes ]>

elements.name: _sharp
comments: short for <div id='${wzName}' [...]> ...

elements.name: _js
comments: When has no children is short for
html4: <script src="${wzName}" type="text/javascript" [ attributes ]></script>
html5: <script src="${wzName}"></script>
When has children is the root of an inline script ( script html element )

elements.name: jsBabel
comments: When has no children is short for
html5: <script src="${wzName}" type="text/babel"></script>
When has children is the root of an inline script ( script html element )

elements.name: statement
comments: The base class of a javascript statement in an html ittf document

elements.name: _css
comments: When has no children is short for <link href="${wzName}" rel="stylesheet" [ attributes ]>
When has children is the root of an inline stylesheet ( style html element )

elements.name: rule

statements.name: call
statements.value: retval.push({ name: p.name() + '-' + p_nested.name(), value: p_nested.value() })

comments: The base abstract rule.
It has a child relation (one-to-many) with itself so one
can declare a tree with unlimited deep.

elements.name: elementRule
comments: The element rule
The wzName contain the selector(s)

elements.name: classRule
comments: The class rule
The wzName contain the selector(s)

elements.name: idRule
comments: The id rule
The wzName contain the selector(s)

elements.name: otherRuleSelector
comments: The wzName contains other selector(s) to add to those of the parent rule
In case of a rule with many selectors allow the declaration on many nodes
Example
< td
+ span
+ li
for: td, span, li, ...

elements.name: property

relations.name: property
comments: Nested property
A generic rule property.
You should find a proper schema element that extends this one for every valid css3 property.
In any case this element is not abstract and can be used for eventual missing properties.
In this case must contain a name-value pair separated by a blank: name is
the property name and value is the property value.

elements.name: _text
comments: The wzName becomes a TEXTNODE rewritten inline in the output document.

elements.name: _textLF
comments: The wzName becomes a TEXTNODE rewritten in the output document followed by a LF char.

elements.name: comment
comments: The wzName is the comment text.

elements.name: _title
comments: The title html element.
The title tag is ambiguous it can be both a global attribute and a child element.

elements.name: _style
comments: The html style element.
The style tag is ambiguous it can be both a global attribute and a child element.

elements.name: lorem
comments: the wzName = count
